Your current setup looks mostly correct, but there are a few adjustments needed to ensure the `className` is applied correctly. The `className` prop for the `Link` component expects a string, but you are using it inside the `Link` element, which does not take `className` as a prop. Instead, the `className` should be applied to an anchor (`<a>`) tag inside the `Link`.

Here's the corrected code with the modification: 

```jsx
import Link from "next/link";
import { useRouter } from "next/router"; // Changed here for useRouter hook
import React, { useState } from 'react';

// ... Icons import

export const navData = [
  // ... Your nav data
];

const MobileNav = () => {
  const { pathname } = useRouter(); // Changed here to use the useRouter hook
  const [isNavVisible, setIsNavVisible] = useState(false);
  const toggleNav = () => {
      setIsNavVisible(!isNavVisible);
  };

  return (
    <>
        <button
            // ... Your button code
        </button>
      <nav className={`flex flex-col items-left gap-y-4 mb-0 py-6 px-12 bg-matte border border-accent rounded-3xl w-60 fixed top-1/4 left-1/2 -translate-x-1/2 -translate-y-1/2 ${isNavVisible ? 'visible' : 'hidden'}`}>
        {navData.map((link, i) => (
            // The Link component from Next.js doesn't accept a className. Instead, you pass the className to the child <a> tag.
            <Link href={link.path} key={i}>
              {/* The anchor (<a>) tag will receive the className */}
              <a className={`relative flex items-center group hover:text-accent transition-all duration-300 ${link.path === pathname ? "text-accent" : ""}`}>
                <link.Icon className="text-lg" aria-hidden="true" />
                <span className="nav-label block text-md text-left mt-1 mx-3 capitalize">{link.name}</span>
              </a>
            </Link>
        ))}
        </nav>
    </>
  );
};

export default MobileNav;
```

With the modified `Link` component, the `className` now correctly applies the `text-accent` class to the anchor tag when the current path matches the `link.path`. Make sure that `text-accent` is a valid Tailwind class or your own custom class that applies the desired styling for the active link.

Note: I've replaced `usePathname` with `useRouter` from `next/router`, which is more commonly used for accessing the current route's pathname. Make sure that your `text-accent` class is defined in your CSS/Tailwind CSS configuration.

In recent versions of Next.js (starting from version 12.2.0), the handling of the `Link` component has changed slightly, where it now wraps the anchor (`<a>`) tag automatically for improved accessibility and convenience. This change helps route navigation happen seamlessly and enforces consistent accessibility behavior.

This error occurs because an explicit anchor (`<a> `) tag is nested inside the `Link` component, which is no longer allowed without specifying `legacyBehavior`.

The correct way to use the `Link` component now is to exclude the `<a>` tag:

```jsx
import Link from "next/link";
import { useRouter } from "next/router";
import React, { useState } from 'react';

// ... Icons import

export const navData = [
  // ... Your nav data
];

const MobileNav = () => {
  const { pathname } = useRouter();
  const [isNavVisible, setIsNavVisible] = useState(false);
  const toggleNav = () => {
      setIsNavVisible(!isNavVisible);
  };

  return (
    <>
        <button
            // ... Your button code
        </button>
      <nav className={`... ${isNavVisible ? 'visible' : 'hidden'}`}>
        {navData.map((link, i) => (
          <Link href={link.path} key={i}>
            { /* Apply the classes directly to the child inside the Link */ }
            <a className={`relative flex items-center group hover:text-accent transition-all duration-300 ${link.path === pathname ? "text-accent" : ""}`}>
              <link.Icon className="text-lg" aria-hidden="true" />
              <span className="nav-label block text-md text-left mt-1 mx-3 capitalize">{link.name}</span>
            </a>
          </Link>
        ))}
      </nav>
    </>
  );
};

export default MobileNav;
```

Now, you are wrapping the content inside the `Link` component with the `<a>` tag without setting the `href` attribute on it, and instead setting the `href` on the `Link` component directly as per the new behavior of Next.js.

This will fix the unhandled runtime error for invalid usage of the `Link` component with nested `<a>` child. Remember that the `text-accent` class should be a defined class in your styling setup to apply the desired text color.
